article.headline: Mor scores career-high 18 points
article.linkText: Boyer breaks Wisconsin-Green Bay long distance mark in win
article.story:
GREEN BAY, Wis. (AP) -- Sara Boyer broke the school career
3-point record, and Tiffany Mor scored a career-high 18 points to
lead No. 21 Wisconsin-Green Bay to an 86-53 victory over Detroit on
Saturday.

	   Green Bay (11-2, 3-0 Horizon League) overcame a sluggish start
to pull away with a 56-point second half. The Phoenix committed 14
turnovers in the first half and trailed 37-34 with 17:37 left in
the game before outscoring the Titans 39-8 over the next 13
minutes.

	   Boyer buried four 3-pointers, all in the second half, on her way
to 16 points. She now has 120 career 3-pointers, eclipsing the
previous record of 117 set by Trisha Ebel in 2001.

	   Mor came off the bench and went 8-for-8 from the floor as the
Phoenix shot 55 percent for the game.

	   Boyer started the deciding run with her record-breaking
3-pointer.

	   Lori Wild scored 16 points off the bench for Detroit and Caitie
Goddard added 15. But Sara Crum and Nicole Anaejionu, Detroit's two
leading scorers, combined for just 10 points for the Titans (3-9,
1-1).

	   Anaejionu played just nine minutes because of foul trouble. She
committed her fourth foul with 17:03 remaining and finished with
four points.

	   The Phoenix had four players in double figures. Abby Scharlow
scored 12 points and Chandra Johnson had 11, while Kristy Loiselle
came close to the school's first triple-double with 10 rebounds,
eight points and eight assists.
